571. J Belg Soc Radiol. 2017 Apr 25;101(1):22. doi: 10.5334/jbr-btr.1275.

Extensive Cervico-Thoraco-Abdominal Attacks of Angioedema: CT Diagnosis in Two 
Unusual Cases.

Coulier B(1), Montfort L(1), Vandezande LM(1), Bafort AC(1), Gogoase M(1).

Author information:
(1)Clinique Saint-Luc, Bouge, BE.

Angioedema (AE) classically manifests as an acute transient swelling of 
extra-visceral spaces, subcutaneous and submucosal tissues. Sometimes it may be 
a life-threatening condition. The causes are numerous, and the common 
denominator is an increased vascular permeability allowing diffusion or 
extravasation of fluid from the vascular bed to the interstitial space. The 
severity of AE is related to the cause, body location, and extension. We hereby 
report two very unusual cases characterized by a massive attack of AE from the 
left cervical area to the pelvis through the length of the mediastinum and axial 
posterior retroperitoneum. The diagnosis was established by CT. The first case 
was found related to drug intake, and the second appeared idiopathic.

